The federal government says it will bring the full wrath of the law to bear on employers who violate the rights of their employees under the guise of the COVID-19 pandemic. Minister of Labour and Employment, Dr. Chris Ngige, handed the threat while speaking at a webinar organised by the Abuja Office of the ILO on the impact of COVID-19, and the rights of migrant workers in Nigeria. Dr Ngige says it was wrong for employers to cut the salaries of employees or terminate their appointments without holding negotiations with the workers to see why such measures became inevitable. “We got reports of three states that did this and we have called them to revert and do the right thing,” the minister said. While calling on the Nigerian Employers Consultative Forum, NECA, to report erring employers to his ministry, the labour minister also announced plans to review licenses of labour outsourcing firms, to ensure that workers are not exposed to indecent work conditions. He denied reports that COVID-19 palliatives were given to portfolio firms instead of genuine employers of labour, adding that interventions by the Central Bank of Nigeria, CBN Bank of Industry, Federal Mortgage Bank of Nigeria, SMEDAN, etc, were given to known and functional business entities. The minister further expressed concern that over 60 percent of the labour force are in the informal sector, saying that there was need to formalise as many informal sectors, so that they can be captured for any intervention from the government. Earlier, director general of NECA, Dr Timothy Olawale, represented by Mr Wale Smart, urged employers not to consider laying off and salary cut as an immediate option to cope with the negative impact of COVID-19. Also speaking, general secretary, Nigerian Labour Congress, Emmanuel Ugboaja, emphasised the need to protect the rights of migrant workers and to carry them along in palliative measures, to cushion the impact of COVID-19.  